SIMPLE: immerse
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Immerse
<hw>Im*merse"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>immersus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>immergere</ets>. See
<er>Immerge</er>.]</ety> <def>Immersed; buried; hid; sunk.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Things <xex>immerse</xex> in matter.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Immerse</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Immerse
<hw>Im*merse"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Immersed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Immersing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To plunge into
anything that surrounds or covers, especially into a fluid; to dip; to
sink; to bury; to immerge.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Deep <qex>immersed</qex> beneath its whirling wave.</q> <rj><qau>J
Warton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>More than a mile <qex>immersed</qex> within the wood.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To baptize by immersion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To engage deeply; to engross the attention of; to
involve; to overwhelm.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The queen <qex>immersed</qex> in such a trance.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is impossible to have a lively hope in another life, and yet be
deeply <qex>immersed</qex> inn the enjoyments of this.</q>
<rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 732 --></p>

<p><ent>Immersed</ent>⟦br⟧
